
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Gnome-keyring yek servis baraye negahdari va modiriyat password-ha, kalid-haye SSH, va sertifikat-ha ast. In komak mikonad ke shoma password-ha-ye khod ra be soorate امن negah دارید va niyazi nist har dafe anha ra vared konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `gnome-keyring-daemon --start`  --> 🚀 Baraye ejra kardane daemon gnome-keyring dar background.
    🔹 `seahorse` --> 🔑 Baraye modiriyat grafiki password-ha va kalid-haye negahdashte shodeh.
    🔹 `ssh-add` --> 🔐 Baraye ezafe kardane kalid-haye SSH be gnome-keyring.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ gnome-keyring-daemon --start
    🔹 Shoru kardane daemon baraye negahdari password-ha.

    $ seahorse
    🔹 Baz kardane barnameh grafiki baraye modiriyat password-ha.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa
    🔹 Vaghti ke password-e SSH key khasteh shod, in password dar gnome-keyring zakhireh mishavad ta dafeye bad az shoma khasteh nashavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    Gnome-keyring is a service to store and manage passwords, SSH keys, and certificates. It helps you securely store your passwords and avoids having to enter them repeatedly.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `gnome-keyring-daemon --start` --> 🚀 To run the gnome-keyring daemon in the background.
    🔹 `seahorse` --> 🔑 To graphically manage stored passwords and keys.
    🔹 `ssh-add` --> 🔐 To add SSH keys to the gnome-keyring.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ gnome-keyring-daemon --start
    🔹 Starts the daemon for storing passwords.

    $ seahorse
    🔹 Opens the graphical application for password management.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa
    🔹 When prompted for the SSH key password, this password will be stored in the gnome-keyring, so you are not prompted again next time.
